{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638506","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638506"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:54:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:54:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17716"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17716","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17716"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10430"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72463"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10430"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17716"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57933"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10192"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24369"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24565"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72463","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72463"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EHair colour is determined by the type and amount of melanin pigments produced within hair follicles.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism determining natural hair colour?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rate of hair growth and replacement","Density of hair follicles in scalp","Amount of keratin protein in hair shaft","Ratio of eumelanin to pheomelanin production","Concentration of blood vessels around follicle"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENatural hair colour is primarily determined by the \u003Cstrong\u003Eratio of eumelanin to pheomelanin production\u003C/strong\u003E by melanocytes in the hair follicle. Eumelanin produces brown and black pigments, while pheomelanin produces red and yellow pigments. The balance between these two types of melanin is regulated by melanocortin-1 receptor signalling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERate of hair growth and replacement\u003C/strong\u003E - The speed at which hair grows and replaces itself does not influence the production of melanin pigments or the resulting hair colour.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDensity of hair follicles in scalp\u003C/strong\u003E - While follicle density affects the appearance of hair thickness, it has no impact on the pigmentation of individual hair strands.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmount of keratin protein in hair shaft\u003C/strong\u003E - Keratin is the structural protein that forms the hair shaft but does not contribute to hair colouration.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConcentration of blood vessels around follicle\u003C/strong\u003E - The blood supply provides nutrients to the hair follicle but does not directly influence melanin production or hair colour.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVariations in melanocortin-1 receptor activity influence the relative amounts of eumelanin and pheomelanin produced, resulting in different hair colours. For example, red hair results from predominantly pheomelanin production, while dark hair contains more eumelanin.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Melanocytes in hair follicles produce melanin pigments that determine hair colour.","Eumelanin produces brown and black colours while pheomelanin produces red and yellow colours.","The ratio of eumelanin to pheomelanin is regulated by melanocortin-1 receptor signalling."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57933"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17716"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57933"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T20:54:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T20:59:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10430"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72463"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"49